# HCDE 530 — Cursor agent rules

## Scope and edits
- Change only what the assignment or user asked for; avoid drive-by refactors or unrelated files.
- Do not delete files or run destructive git commands unless the user explicitly requests it.

## Python (course scripts)
- Resolve paths to bundled data with `Path(__file__).resolve().parent` (or equivalent) so scripts run from any working directory.
- Open text with `encoding="utf-8"`; keep printed output readable on Windows terminals.
- Validate text before `int()` / numeric work: use `.isdigit()` or similar checks; skip or return `None` for bad values instead of crashing.
- For sorting that must pick “top” by a metric, state intent in code or comments (e.g. `reverse=True` for descending) so direction bugs are obvious.
- After substantive edits, run the script to confirm it completes without errors.

## Documentation and readability
- Prefer clear names and small, single-purpose functions over clever one-liners.
- Add inline comments on major sections when the logic supports a learning goal: say *why* something exists (e.g. a word-to-number map), not only *what* it stores.
- Use short docstrings on non-trivial functions to describe inputs, outputs, and edge cases (empty values, skipped rows).

## Data cleaning
- Skip rows missing required fields (e.g. name, role) before aggregates; normalize categorical text consistently (e.g. casing) and note tradeoffs in comments when normalization could affect downstream joins.
